content.text:
Done. The fix is implemented and verified clean.

**What I changed** — `apps/web/src/config/openui/components/DocumentEditor.tsx`: added an effect right after `useEditor(...)` that re-applies the streamed body to the editor when it grows, guarded by a `lastBodyRef` so user edits aren't clobbered once streaming settles:

```tsx
const lastBodyRef = React.useRef(body);
React.useEffect(() => {
  if (!editor || body === lastBodyRef.current) return;
  lastBodyRef.current = body;
  editor.commands.setContent(body, false);
}, [editor, body]);
```

**Root cause (verified through the full chain):** the OpenUI parser auto-closes unterminated strings during streaming (`parser.js:129`), so `TextDocumentView` receives a *progressively growing partial body*. tiptap's `useEditor({ content })` only applies content once at creation, so the editor froze on the first partial chunk — the card chrome rendered fine but the body was cut off. It affects any live-streamed `TextDocument`, not just onboarding; the fix is in the shared component so it covers both.

**Checks:** `nx run web:type-check` ✅ and `nx lint web` ✅ (the 6 lint warnings are pre-existing in other files; none touch this change).

**Remaining (live confirmation, your call):** the static proof is solid, but to see it end-to-end, run `nx dev web` + backend and ask GAIA to draft a long document in normal chat — watch the body fill in completely as it streams (that's the same code path as the onboarding run-now demo, just easier to trigger). I didn't run this since it needs the dev servers and a backend.

One housekeeping note: I mistakenly scheduled a fallback wakeup earlier (meant as a safety net for the background jobs). It's harmless and you can ignore it, but flagging it so it's not a surprise.

